2 Run Summary

2.1 General Workflow

Raw reads from individual samples are summarized with FastQC. If the --no-trim option was specified (see samplesheet, below), then raw reads are aligned to the reference genome with HISAT2. If --no-trim was not specified, then the reads are cleaned with Trimmomatic and re-assessed with FastQC, and trimmed reads are aligned to the reference genome with HISAT2. Reads aligning to genes are counted with featureCounts, from the subread package. Raw counts are transformed into counts-per-million with the edgeR package. Genes that are shorter than the specified minimum length (--min-len argument, default 200bp) are pruned from the counts matrix before any differential expression analysis. If experimental groups were supplied, then differential expression analysis is performed with a quasi-likelihood test in edgeR, with a 0.05 false discovery rate correction applied.

2.2 Results and Intermediate Files

2.2.1 Output Directory

The output directory is located at

/scratch.global/konox006/RNAseq_Tutorial_Out

This directory contains final results files and log files for the pipeline. Be sure to save these files if you would like to keep them. However, the pipeline script and samplesheet (reproduced below) are sufficient to recreate all output files. It will just require additional compute time and service units. The following directories are of interest:

  • /scratch.global/konox006/RNAseq_Tutorial_Out/Counts

    Contains raw and CPM-transformed counts for each gene in the supplied GTF annotation.

  • /scratch.global/konox006/RNAseq_Tutorial_Out/DEGs

    Contains a list of significantly differentially expressed genes, if experimental groups were supplied. If differential expression analysis was conducted, but no genes passed thresholds for significance, then the files will only have a header. Pairwise combinations of groups are tested for significance, so this directory may contain multiple files.

  • /scratch.global/konox006/RNAseq_Tutorial_Out/InsertSizeMetrics

    Contains per-sample insert size summaries from Picard tools. The mean, median, and standard deviation are summarized in a table in the "Alignment Summaries" section of this report.

  • /scratch.global/konox006/RNAseq_Tutorial_Out/Logs

    Contains per-sample run logs for read QC, trimming, and alignment. Also contains a log file for counting reads and performing differential expression testing.

  • /scratch.global/konox006/RNAseq_Tutorial_Out/Plots

    Contains PDF vector images of expression summary plots. The plots are also embedded into the "Counts Summaries" subsection of the "Alignment Summaries" section of this report.

2.2.2 Work Directory

The work directory is located at

/scratch.global/konox006/RNAseq_Tutorial_Work

This directory contains intermediate files for the pipeline. Be sure to save these files if you would like to refer to them in the future. However, the pipeline script and samplesheet (reproduced below) are sufficient to recreate all intermediate files for the pipeline. The work directory contains the following:

  • /scratch.global/konox006/RNAseq_Tutorial_Work/allsamples

    Summary files used to generate this report and final BAM files used for generating raw counts.

  • /scratch.global/konox006/RNAseq_Tutorial_Work/singlesamples

    Sub-directories, one for each sample, with FastQC reports, trimmed reads, intermediate SAM and BAM files, and alignment summary files. Refer to these if you would like to see the details of one particular sample. For example, if one sample has unexpected expression values, it may be because the sample is of low quality; this would be apparent in the read quality reports and the alignment summaries that are found in its work directory.

2.3 Pipeline Script

The path to the pipeline script is /scratch.global/konox006/RNAseq_Tutorial_Out/2018-11-19.konox006.bulk_rnaseq.pipeline.sh

The pipeline script is printed below. You may copy and paste the following script into a new plain text document to recreate the analyses run here. Be sure to save it with UNIX line endings (LF rather than CR [Mac] or CRLF [Windows] line endings), or else it will cause errors on Mesabi. Also be sure to turn off "smart quotes" and "smart dashes" on any text editors that you use to paste the following script. Smart quotes and smart dashes are not interpreted correctly by the shell on Mesabi and will also cause errors.

Click to show pipeline script

#!/bin/bash
# Generated by CHURP version 0.0.1
# Generated at 2018-11-19 16:37:09
set -e
set -u
set -o pipefail
user_name="$(id -u -n)"
user_email="${user_name}@umn.edu"
OUTDIR="/scratch.global/konox006/RNAseq_Tutorial_Out"
WORKDIR="/scratch.global/konox006/RNAseq_Tutorial_Work"
DE_SCRIPT="/panfs/roc/groups/14/msistaff/konox006/Soft/CHURP/R_Scripts/summarize_bulk_rnaseq.R"
REPORT_SCRIPT="/panfs/roc/groups/14/msistaff/konox006/Soft/CHURP/R_Scripts/bulk_rnaseq_report.Rmd"
SAMPLESHEET="/scratch.global/konox006/RNAseq_Tutorial_Out/2018-11-19.konox006.bulk_rnaseq.samplesheet.txt"
PURGE="true"
PIPE_SCRIPT="$( cd "$( dirname "${BASH_SOURCE[0]}" )" >/dev/null && pwd )/$(basename $0)"
single_id=$(qsub -q mesabi -m abe -M "${user_email}"  -o "${OUTDIR}" -e "${OUTDIR}" -l "mem=12000mb,nodes=1:ppn=4,walltime=7200" -t 1-8 -v "SampleSheet=${SAMPLESHEET},PURGE=${PURGE}" /panfs/roc/groups/14/msistaff/konox006/Soft/CHURP/PBS/bulk_rnaseq_single_sample.pbs || exit 1)
summary_id=$(qsub -q mesabi -m abe -M "${user_email}"  -o "${OUTDIR}" -e "${OUTDIR}" -W "depend=afterokarray:${single_id}" -v "SampleSheet=${SAMPLESHEET},MINLEN=200,MINCPM=1.0,RSUMMARY=${DE_SCRIPT},PIPE_SCRIPT=${PIPE_SCRIPT},BULK_RNASEQ_REPORT=${REPORT_SCRIPT}" /panfs/roc/groups/14/msistaff/konox006/Soft/CHURP/PBS/run_summary_stats.pbs || exit 1)
echo "Output and logs will be written to ${OUTDIR}"
echo "Emails will be sent to ${user_email}"
echo "Single samples job array ID: ${single_id}"
echo "Summary job ID: ${summary_id}"

4.4.1 Number of Expressed Features

This plot shows the number of features (genes) that have at least one read mapping to them.

4.4.2 Expression in Counts-per-million

Shown below is a distribution of expression values as log2(1+CPM). CPM (counts-per-million) is a transformation of raw counts that accounts for the number of fragments sequenced in the library, like FPKM. It does not account for gene length like FPKM, however. You can compare CPM values for the same gene across samples, but do not compare CPM values for different genes in the same sample.

5 DEG Testing

If experimental groups were supplied, we test for differential expression among them with a quasi-likelihood test (using glmQLFit in edgeR). We apply a 0.05 false discovery rate correction to the differential expression tests. If you did not supply experimental groups, then this section will mostly be empty.
